Lake covered with patches of green algae.
DEEPEST SPOT NEAR CENTER OF LAKE

Algae is dense- blue-green and smelly along some shorelines. It has lasted longer during the fall than any time during eleven years of monitoring. September was a record setting warm month. Could that cause the increase in algal growth

This is our first time to do D.O.  We have always looked into the water and declared "brown" for water color.  Now- aware of the training to use the Secchi disc- the water appears to have a green tint.
Bog makes its appearance near the south end of the flowage.

column1: Downed trees from windstorm along southwest shoreline.

column2: Lake is calm; sun trying to peek through the clouds.
blue green algae is the worst we have seen and lasting late into the Fall
Depth finder showed 24 ft. and we watched a loon take flight. The thrills of being a water quality monitor!
A cloudless blue sky "delicious" summer day. The floating bog has surfaced!
Lake level is up a little- although the dam keeps the level within a specified number of inches.
Spring arriving slowly. Today is sunny- calm. Loons have returned. Grands- Spencer and Baylee- are helpers.
Lake visitors were helpers - Rodney and Lisa.
Calm- blue sky morning. Eagle on a birch on Sand Island.
Little bits of algae on surface. Pristine fall reflections.
Cloudy- last day for the boat. The dock comes out today.
Bog has surfaced. Great Blue Heron sighted. QA/QC Sampling today with blank and duplicate samples.
Blue-green algae. Floating bog has separated into three pieces.
Memorial Day week-end - many boaters - happy to have dam repaired and lake filled again!
Eagle in treetop watching over the flowage
Clouds rolled away since being at Central Basin
Floating bog didn't surface this year
Lake is resting after almost 10" of rain and flooding with washout upriver at Colton Dam. Dock sections floated and are caught along shoreline.
Bog has surfaced! Some algae at south end of Flowage.
